As for jumping through a lot of hoops; it's never that difficult for using second-hand shipping companies. It's as simple as finding a proxy service you like, such as JapanRabbit, making an account and adding a card for charges. Then you can simply go to the product you want, copy the link to the actual item and paste it in the service's provided purchase bar. You'll get taken to a page that lists the price, which may or may not need adjusting, and you might be prompted to copy paste the actual item name as well. These services walk you through the process simply enough, and as long as you have the money, it's as easy as keeping up to date on your emails.

>>68062444
>So some expanse or insight into who they are through dialogue, quirks, and actions during situations, right?
Yes. They were born, grew up, had relationships, learned shit, lived a culture. They are a full person with a different perspective who will react to situations in different and novel ways, sometimes ways you wouldn't expect from a surface evaluation. Give them something, literally anything, to imply this fact. It doesn't have to be some deep angst or whatever but there has to be something, somewhere in them, that makes them not just a clone of whatever culture or group they come from/most identify with.
The hard part is making those tiny nuances and occasional subversions not stereotypical themselves.
You can only generalize so much. Someone might play to whatever image you've built in your head of them the majority of the time but there should be something that adds a new facet to how you interpret that painting (granted, with real people, it's likely some negative shit that can make them look far worse but if it's your dog and pony show then you get to make it positive or at least only mildly negative from a certain point of view)

To expand on this let's use an example. Let's pic a random pic for the character.
Her personality is stereotypical bad girl. She smokes to look cool, likes motorcycles, swears casually but gets quiet when she is serious. Bog basic dome a dozen.

Let's say her objective is romantic because /hmofa/. Let's say her objective is to form a live in situation with a human male she has become smitten with working at a truck stop convince store on her favorite highway. She yearns for his meat but doesn't know how to communicate to someone so straight laced and is afraid of scaring him off. She spends a lot of time driving the highway in front of his store compntemplating this.

For a goal we'll need a plot, let's rip Killer Dozer and that Charlie Sheen movie Wraith and say that a possessed Tank has been rampaging up and down a highway. Our character gets caught behind military barricades and is terrorized by the ghost tank. Thus she has the goal: Not be killed by ghost tank.

And we have a character: A bad girl wants to bunk up with human male, not die to ghost tank. Let's say in this story she is a bitch but after killing the ghost tank and seeing her trepidations at forming a bond with a human male. She kills the ghost tank and we like her by the end because she faced her problems, killed ghost tank, and now has a human bf riding bitch.

There you go, a character.
